The paper is their second contribution to the theory of tax evasion – an area where their work is most highly cited and is having an impact on policy, following presentations of their research at HMRC. The paper draws on the expertise of both authors in different areas: that of al-Nowaihi in tax evasion and prospect theory, and that of Dhami in public economics. This paper would not have been possible without the separate contributions of each author.

They started working on this paper long before Denicolò joined Leicester. The research builds on previous results independently obtained by the authors: Zanchettin (JEMS 2006) shows that more  intense competition may lead to an increase in the most efficient firm’s profits, whereas Denicolò (EER 2001) develops an endogenous model where the innovator may stay active for several periods. These are two key ingredients of the present paper, which would not have been possible without the separate contributions of each author

Les Français sont-ils prudents? Patrimoine et risque sur le marché du travail
EnglishAbstract: Precautionary savings have been advanced as one of the main drivers of wealth accumulation. However its quantification remains elusive: simulation methods that calibrate life-cycle models on income data find a 50% share of precautionary assets in total assets, while econometric studies suggest a range of 1-20%. Our study quantifies the precautionary saving motive from the INSEE’s 2004 Household Assets Survey exploiting variation in individual responses to questions eliciting quantitatively the subjective evolution of household income risk over a five year horizon, including the probability of losing one’s job. The precautionary-saving motive seldom exceeds 10% of financial/total wealth
